title: For Sale/Trade:  Want to trade, 50+ y/o Vintage Saddle, Handtooled Leather, Show Quality for Pistol
postcontent:
I don't ride, I don't know about saddles, this is a family heirloom that I just don't have a need for, nor would it fit my decor for display.

It is in beautiful condition. Looks as if it was only used maybe one season. The tooling is amazing. For the price I'm asking, you'd make minimum wage if you were the one to hand tool this.

I looked it over and found a maker's mark. It's a Simco, says Est 1933 (I know that's not when it was made). But it was probably between 1960 and 1970. Simco's of early provenance appear to be more popular than most other vintage saddles. It is a Model 35. Definitely old.

You could definitely use this saddle, but honestly I think it would be better on display.

I'm very fair. We'll trade against both lows... both averages (most fair and what I listed) or both highs. High value for this saddle is $1200. AND APPRECIATING.

But, I'd still rather have a pistol, than a beautiful saddle.

Hopefully someone feels exactly opposite?

title: For Sale:  Glock 19, Fraternal Order of Police 1989 Inaugural, Washington D.C.
postcontent:
This Glock 19, is a true closet queen. These, with the FOP engraving on the side, were available to members of the Metropolitan Police Department, Washington, DC in 1989 when the department converted from revolvers to the Glocks. These were not issued by the government, they were offered thru the FOP lodge from Glock. 

Departmental communication in those days was by "Teletype" machines. I have an original teletype, dated May 30, 1989, announcing the arrival of the Glocks ordered prior to March 1, 1989. I cannot imagine that there is another nut out there that has this message from 1989...my bet is that this is the only one that exists and it links this gun historically.

This pistol was made in April 1989 and after I first picked it up on June 1, 1989, I fired 20 rounds thru it. Glock then recalled the pistols to change a spring inside to adjust the trigger pull, so I sent mine off to Glock and after they serviced it, I put it away and never fired it. So it is in truly new condition.

Included, with the gun (which has regular white sights, not the glow type) and teletype message, is the original box, manual, two 15 round magazines, a magazine loading assist tool, a Glock #45 holster, original unused bore brush and cleaning rod. I also have the original invoice from Glock for the originial purchase dated May 1989.

Please make sure the magazines are legal in your state, if I find they are not, I guess I will have to send the gun with no magazines and no refund or apology...hope you understand that I don't want to violate any laws.

I am not a FFL holder, so $50 shipping from my local FFL holder to yours, or face to face with no charge to a fellow resident of Virginia
